icial reports, to the U.S. Supreme Court's adoption in the early nineteenth century of generally unanimous opinions. While this institutional base was firmly established by the twentieth century, Popkin suggests that the modern U.S. judicial opinion has reverted-in some respects-to one in which each judge expresses an individual point of view. Ultimately, he concludes that a shift from an authoritative to a more personal and exploratory individual style of writing opinions is consistent with a more democratic judicial institution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aJudicial opinionsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aJudicial opinionsxLanguagexHistoryxUnited States. 0aJudicial opinionszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aJudicial opinionszUnited StatesxLanguagexHistory. 0aJudicial processxHistoryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aJudicial processzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLAW / Judicial Power.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aPopkin.  aRepublic.  aWilliam.  abeen.  aearly.  aexamines.  afrom.  ahave.  ajudges.  ajudicial.  aopinion.  aopinions.  apresent.  apresented.  astudy.  asweeping.  athis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814768419423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814768419/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK